title: For Sale/Trade:  22 Long Rifle Ammo for Maverick 88 (5+5+5+5)
postcontent:
I would like to trade the 22LR ammo in the photo for a Mossberg Maverick 88 12-gauge with an 18.5" barrel. I know I can't get a Glock out of it, but I am looking for this $150 shotgun for HD and because I can throw a turkey choke on it if and when I need to take it hunting (once every few years). My .410, 20-gauge, 12-gauge, and 30-30, were lost in a house fire a few years ago and I never got around to replacing them.

If I were to sell these outright, I would have to charge much more than the value I am giving them here, since I would have to include gas and time (LOTS of looking). I would not feel right even offering to sell them for the prices I would have to ask. So they are not for sale.

I am not trying to overprice the ammo or take advantage of the "shortage" of 22 long rifle ammunition. I just have an equal value of ammo I would like to trade before I start searching, comparing prices, and ultimately shelling out the money for the Maverick.  For those who don't like the ammo-for-guns trades, keep in mind I am looking to trade around $150 of ammo for a $150 shotgun, even if you got it at a gun show for $130, which I consider to be different from trying to charge $55 for a $25 box of Federal bulk.  This is my figuring:

5xRemington SubSonic + 5xRWS Target Rifle + 5xCCI Stinger + 5xCCI Mini-Mag =
5x$5 + 5x$8 + 5x$10 +5x$10 = $165

Stingers and Mini-Mags can be had for a little less at Wal-Mart, but I wish you luck in finding them at WM. They definitely do not carry Subsonic or RWS rounds (I recommend the German-made RWS's - they are the most accurate of all listed).

If you'd like to get rid of your Maverick, or perhaps something else, let me know what you have in mind. The ammo is not for sale - only trade.

postcontent:
This is an Hk clone.
Chambered in 7.62x51/308.

I've seen these rifles sell used for as low as $564, as high as $900.
The rifle has a hk91 tri rail handguards. $119
As well as as Magpul precision adjustable stock. G3 model. $255
The scope is mediocre. Illuminates red/green. But is mounted by the g3 picatany rail.
The previous owner used an adhesive (very well) to hold it steady. You are still able to use the adjustable rear iron sights.
I have quite a few mags, (they cost like $5 online) I think 12 of them.

I have the original brown furniture. And a green set. 

Now the more honest part.
The paint job looks good from a yard away. It's a black/white digital urban camo.
However (done by precise owner) is a 4/10 at best. 
The rifle double fires cheap crap ammo.
There is nothing wrong with it, however investigating it I learned the blowback operation of the rifle is to violent, the cheap ammo is struck and primer ignites during the seating of the round.
I put a lesser firing pin spring in it to resolve the issue. But to be safe I stopped buying the cheap stuff (like $5-10 a box) 
Anything sold buy Winchester, Remington, blazer all work flawlessly.
And usually run $15 a box or up.
Easy remedy.

title: For Sale:  Springfield Armory FAL SAR-4800 Match Like SAR-48
location: Walnut Cove, Winston Salem, North Carolina
postcontent: For sale is a used FAL rifle, made in Brazil by FN licensed manufacturer Imbel. This is a sweet shooting gun! Closest thing you can get to an authentic Belgian-made rifle. Top quality, not a mixmaster "parts gun". Today these guns, when you can find them, run anywhere from $700-$2000 with the premium prices going of course to the SAR-48 rifles, especially the Bush and Match variants. This was a SAR-4800 SPORTER MODEL IN .308 Win. cal., Mfg. 1990-1998. The fugly thumbhole stock added to comply with the Assault Weapons Ban (BOO!) is gone, and it has the correct pistol grip and buttstock of the SAR-48. This is an authentic model of the Belgian semi-auto FAL/LAR rifle, 21 in. barrel, has two 20-shot mags. Just about every western military adopted FN's FAL in the 1960s. More than three million of the guns were made, not only in Belgium, but also in England, Australia, Austria, Brazil, and others. This earned it the moniker of 'The Free World's Right Arm" which it held until fading to history in the 1990s. With the dawn of the 1980s, people were very interested in the FAL design. FN had imported the guns into the country in a special semi-auto only variant in the 1970s but this supply was now cut off. Giving the public what they wanted, Springfield contracted with licensed-FAL producer Imbel in Brazil to make a semi-auto metric pattern rifle for the US import market. Labeled and marked as the SAR-48, this rifle was as close to a Belgian made real deal FAL as you could get, other than the fact that it was semi-auto only. From the barrel to the gas piston action to the grips and mags, the gun was authentic. It was imported into the country in three subvariants from 1985-89. This included the standard 21-inch barrel model, a 18-inch barreled "Bush Rifle" and an Israeli "Match" pattern rifle with a heavy barrel, mounted bipod, flash-hider, ribbed forward furniture and flip-up plate on the butt of the stock. The gun was a hit but after 1990 had to be changed to comply with the coming Assault Weapons Ban. Sold as the SAR-4800 Sporter, this was the exact same gun as the standard SAR-48 was with a few tweaks. Gone was the evil buttstock, replaced by the abomination that was the thumbhole plastic stock. Likewise, this model was also offered in .5.56/.223 to appeal to the masses who felt 7.62 NATO was too stout. After 1994 when the AWB took effect, it was sold with just a 10-round mag, although any metric FAL mag would work in its well. Sadly, importation of even these guns was stopped in 1997.

http://civilresponse.net

This class qualifies for your Minnesota permit to carry certificate which is also valid in other states like Florida, Arizona, Wisconsin and Iowa, to name a few.

Learn more than the minimum that is required by state law to legally carry a firearm in public. The classes at Civil Response Firearms Training LLC offer students valuable information, such as; avoiding violent encounters, how to clear common firearm malfunctions, cleaning and maintenance of firearms, advice on choosing a handgun, less lethal alternatives, accessories, and much more.  We hope that our course can be educational and be found to be extremely valuable even if you never plan on carrying a handgun.

If you need a handgun for the shooting qualification, we have some available to use free of charge.

There are currently no indoor ranges in the area, so please dress accordingly and bring appropriate gear for the weather.
